name: Jacob Wolf
tweet: And if it fails, our industry won't be doomed. But there will be a set back because some investors and advertisers don't understand that "esports" means multiple games, rather than just some monolith.  Overwatch isn't League of Legends or Counter-Strike. It hasn't aged well.

name: Jacob Wolf
tweet: Overwatch League was able to capitalize on investor FOMO, all while appearing buttoned-up in a way that endemics do not (had several owners tell me this on-the-record). Their pitch used esports as a whole to sell a league built on a game with zero proof of concept.

name: Jacob Wolf
tweet: I don't think Overwatch League will fail in Season 3. It has too much money behind it too. But I do think many homestands will underperform, teams and the league will overspend and media rights and sponsorships will be smaller deals with more entities.

name: Jacob Wolf
tweet: I've given the league credit where it's due, such as in sponsorships and media rights, where in Season 1 in particular, it sold well above its weight.  But from the beginning, the expectations were set way too high and budget estimates for teams and league were set way too low.

name: Jacob Wolf
tweet: After those reports, I went on several talk shows and spoke to the high expectation that a number like that sets for esports and how I did not feel it was fitting of where we were as an industry in 2017. And for Overwatch, specifically, I still don't think it warrants that.

name: Jacob Wolf
tweet: But, to say that I was not critical of it before now, is wrong.  No other reporter has the insights on that league like I do – I was the first to report the accurate buy-in numbers ($20 million for Season 1) and then subsequently 9 of 12 teams who would participate.

name: Jacob Wolf
tweet: Here's some context, given some recent backlash on my thoughts on Overwatch League and the precarious position they're in.  Like most, I want Overwatch League to succeed. It has brought some very important eyeballs, particularly from the investment side, to esports.

name: David Zhou
tweet: It sounds weird at first: how does a cycle that runs twice as long use less water or energy? The trick, apparently, is in how water is sprayed, the rate it’s spraying, how water is heated, how dishes are dries, and a change in how detergents actually clean.

name: David Zhou
tweet: The priority list for dishwashers to meet Energy Star standards is water usage, electricity usage, total runtime, in that order. It makes sense. For many people, the load runs in the background, you might not even notice an extra hour
